        <h1>MiniFCU Interface Protocol & Emulator</h1>
        <p>
            <strong>Hardware Firmware Version:</strong> 20251113<br>
            <strong>Protocol Revision:</strong> 3.1 (Updated Dec 2025)
        </p>
        <p>This document details the serial protocol used by the <strong>miniFCU</strong> autopilot interface (A320 style), based on reverse-engineering of the communication between the hardware and the official Windows software.</p>
    </header>

    <section id="hardware">
        <h2>1. Hardware Interface</h2>
        <p>The miniFCU utilizes a <strong>CH340 USB-to-Serial</strong> bridge. To communicate with the device using an ESP32, Python, or Linux, ensure your serial connection matches these settings exactly:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Baud Rate:</strong> 9600 bps</li>
            <li><strong>Data Bits:</strong> 8</li>
            <li><strong>Parity:</strong> None</li>
            <li><strong>Stop Bits:</strong> 1</li>
            <li><strong>Flow Control:</strong> None</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="alert">
            <strong>CRITICAL:</strong> You MUST set <code>DTR=True</code> and <code>RTS=True</code> immediately upon opening the serial connection. This signal is required to wake up the microcontroller.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="initialization">
        <h2>2. Initialization Sequence (Handshake)</h2>
        <p>The device enters a locked state upon power-up. It will not respond to button presses or display data until the following handshake sequence is completed sequentially.</p>

        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Step</th>
                    <th>Direction</th>
                    <th>Data (ASCII)</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>1</td>
                    <td>Host &rarr; HW</td>
                    <td><code>C,</code></td>
                    <td><strong>Connect Request</strong>. Clears the line.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td></td>
                    <td>HW &rarr; Host</td>
                    <td><code>901;956;959;</code></td>
                    <td><em>Response: Device Firmware/Module IDs.</em></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>2</td>
                    <td>Host &rarr; HW</td>
                    <td><code>9,C,c,</code></td>
                    <td><strong>Command Mode Config</strong>.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>3</td>
                    <td>Host &rarr; HW</td>
                    <td><code>7,%0,i,y,w,o,N,</code></td>
                    <td><strong>Low Level Enable</strong>. Activates I/O flags.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>4</td>
                    <td>Host &rarr; HW</td>
                    <td><code>7,&,</code></td>
                    <td><strong>Pre-Calibration</strong>.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>5</td>
                    <td>Host &rarr; HW</td>
                    <td><em>[Magic String]</em></td>
                    <td><strong>Sensor Calibration</strong>. (See below).</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>6</td>
                    <td>Host &rarr; HW</td>
                    <td><em>[EFIS String]</em></td>
                    <td><strong>EFIS Initialization</strong>. (See below).</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Required Initialization Strings</h3>
        <p>These strings are extracted from Firmware 20251113 and are required for correct operation.</p>

        <h4>Step 5 (Magic String / Calibration)</h4>
        <pre><code>Q400,K100,-99,+10,n49000,b100,[6000,]-6000,Z9900,X-9900,I,Y,W,O,{1,(3248,}2200,=1100,$745,%0,</code></pre>

        <h4>Step 6 (EFIS Unlock & Defaults)</h4>
        <pre><code>w,v,x,s,q,i,d,w,v,p,u,t,l,e,r,B1000,#1013,{1,@1,51,40,30,20,10,00,!0,#1013,Y,</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="heartbeat">
        <h2>3. The "Heartbeat" (Keep-Alive)</h2>
        <p>To keep the display active and poll for user inputs, the Host must send a query command every <strong>200ms - 1000ms</strong>.</p>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Host Command:</strong> <code>6,</code></li>
            <li><strong>Device Response:</strong> <code>99;94;952;962;972;982;</code></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Response Breakdown</h3>
        <p>The response contains status flags followed by the device's unique serial numbers.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><code>99;</code> / <code>94;</code> : <strong>Status Flags</strong> (Alive/Ready).</li>
            <li><code>952;962;972;982;</code> : <strong>Serial Numbers</strong> (Unique to each unit/LCD module).</li>
        </ul>
        <p><em>Developer Note: When parsing the response, read until the newline or semicolon terminator. Do not validate against a fixed string like "94", as the trailing numbers will vary between devices.</em></p>
    </section>

